ce:section.ce:para:
X-ray diffraction (XRD) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM): A 10 mL 18.77 mg/mL CDN, CDN/Au1, 10 mL 13.31 mg/mL CDE, 10 mL 13.64 mg/mL CDN1, CDN1/Au2 were added in the material tray respectively. They were frozen in the cold trap by a drying freezerwith vacuum for 5 h, dried at 0.1 Pa for 24 hoursto obtain solid sample, then it was placed in a test dish and tested to record the XRD (Fig. 3
                        ). The XRDof CDN (Fig. 3A) indicated a broad peak about 2θ = 24.18 (002) and CDN/Au1 (Fig. S3F) appeared a broad peak at 2θ = 24.94 (002), the corresponding lattice spacing is consistent with the previously studied carbon dots spacing, and demonstrates a well-ordered layered structure and layering law. Then CDN/Au1 gives a narrow peak around 2θ = 30.38 (111), which corresponds to Au nano-carbide. The XRD of CDE (Fig. S3G) gives a broad peak around 2θ = 23.02 (002), which is corresponding to the graphite structure of carbon dots, and gives a diffraction peak around 2θ = 38.52, which is corresponding to N-doped carbon dots of the CDE. For CDN1 (Fig. S3H) gives a diffraction peak around 2θ = 35.12 corresponding to N-doped carbon dots of the CDN1. For CDN1/Au2 (Fig. 3B) gives a diffraction peak around 2θ = 29.52 and 35.1 corresponding to Au nano-carbide and the N-doped carbon dots of the CDN1/Au2 
                        [40,41]. TEMs of CDN and CDN1Au show in Fig. 3C and D, with an average size of 8 and 10 nm respectively.
